</a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury </em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work. </strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects! </strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy </strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns! </strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats </em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals! </strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts </strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;3h 31m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-15-the-half-circle-skirt-where-to-put-the-joining-seam/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-15-the-half-circle-skirt-where-to-put-the-joining-seam/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-04T17:13:29+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-07T18:44:07+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 15. The Half-Circle Skirt. Where to Put the Joining Seam?"><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 15. The Half-Circle Skirt. Where to Put the Joining Seam?"><meta itemprop="description" content="Did you know that the look of the half-circle skirt depends on the position of its side seams? I will prove it to you right now!"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 15. The Half-Circle Skirt. Where to Put the Joining Seam?</h1><p><strong>I want to ask you a question before we start. Did you know that the look of the half-circle skirt depends on the position of its side seams? </strong>I will prove it to you right now!</p><p><strong>I took the full sweep skirt which was cut in the previous tutorial, increased its waist opening radius, and turned it into a half-circle skirt. </strong>The waist opening radius of the full sweep skirt was 6cm. I added another 6cm to make a total of 12cm and imitated a seam in the middle of the back.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2015.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2015.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>In addition, I divided the front and the back of the skirt in four equal sections and marked down at what degrees to the straight lengthwise grain the resulting vertical lines run. </strong></p><p><strong>I joined the selvages and got a central back seam running parallel to the lengthwise grain. </strong></p><p><strong>Positions of all segment lines will be calculated based on the lengthwise grain or the central back seam which corresponds to 0 degrees. </strong>I measure 23 degrees from the lengthwise grain and draw segment (1), measure 45 degrees and draw segment (2), and then draw segments (3) and (4) in the same manner.</p><p><strong>The line going at 45 degrees from the lengthwise grain passes over the supposed princess seam line of the skirt. And the line going at 90 degrees from the lengthwise grain is the front midline which is parallel to the crosswise grain. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2015.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>And now I want to show you </strong>how the positions of lengthwise and crosswise grain (i.e. the way the skirt sits on the wearer) affects the look of the half-circle skirt.</p><p><strong>It is a very important trick widely employed by fashion designers. I am sure you will find it useful. </strong></p><p><strong>We are working with a mock-up so I will demonstrate this trick on the half-scale dress-form put on a spinning tray. </strong></p><p><strong>I put the skirt on the dress-form so as to align the 90 degrees line (crosswise grain) with the front vertical midline. </strong>The bias edges running at 45 degrees from the lengthwise grain are positioned at the sides of the skirt and the lengthwise grain itself runs parallel to the central back seam. As the result, the closure is positioned in the middle of the back.</p><p><strong>Please look at the pictures below and note the way the folds are formed on the skirt put on the wearer in this manner. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2015.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2015.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>There are two folds at the front and three folds at the back. </strong>This way of putting a half-circle skirt on the wearer, with the central back seam parallel to the lengthwise grain, is used when you need to create a transition to a train. A half-circle skirt with a train looks a lot more harmonious with more folds at the back than at the front.</p><p><strong>I adjust the skirt on the dress-form to make the lengthwise grain and the crosswise grain run along the sides of the skirt. </strong>As the result, the 45 degrees bias-cut edges are moved to the middle of the front and the middle of the back. The closure will be installed in the side seam of the skirt in this position.</p><p><strong>Please look at the folds in this case. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2015.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2015.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>There are three folds at the front and three folds at the backs. And they are smoother than in the previous case. </strong></p><p><strong>This means </strong>that the fabric gets distributed rather evenly when the closure of a half-circle skirt is installed in the side seam. The skirt looks the same from the front as it does from the back.</p><p>I would not recommend adding a train in this case because the front is rather full and does not differ from the back.</p><p><strong>The back of the skirt becomes short when you spread it open. There is not enough volume for a train. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2015.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Whereas in the first version </strong>a train will compensate for the excess volume at the back as compared to the front, making the skirt look well-balanced,<strong> in the present case </strong>the front of the skirt will obviously look richer and it will seem as if there were a lot more fabric at the front than at the back.</p><p><strong>This skirt does look harmonious without a train though. </strong></p><p><strong>I turn the skirt so as to position the side seams at 23 degrees from the lengthwise grain.</strong></p><p><strong>Look how different the folds are now. </strong></p><p><strong>You can clearly see two folds at the front of the skirt, but they are very different from the folds we got when the closure was positioned in the middle of the back. </strong>These two folds running down the supposed front princess seam lines are much more pronounced. They run parallel to the crosswise grain (90 degrees) and the bias grain (45 degrees).</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2015.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The back looks different too. There are three folds: one running down the vertical midline and two running down the supposed princess seam lines. </strong>The folds at the back are also more pronounced than they were with the closure in the middle of the back.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2015.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Just look at this skirt! </strong>It seems to be the same from all sides!</p><p><strong>Even the fold at the level of the side seam is very even. </strong></p><p><strong>You would think the closure or the lengthwise grain is positioned in a very non-standard way, but this skirt actually looks the best! </strong></p><p><strong>It will also look great with a train because there are large enough folds at the back and the front looks very neat, too. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2015.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>You should know all these peculiarities of the half-circle skirt and account for them </strong>whenever you are, for example, looking at a picture of a certain skirt struggling to figure out why you can’t make the folds lie as beautifully as in the picture.</p><p><strong>Remember everything I told you and try to turn the skirt around on the dress-form. </strong>You are very likely to find that the answer is hiding in the position of the lengthwise grain!</p><p>Such are the surprising properties of full sweep and half-circle skirts!</p><p>These properties allow you to change the appearance of the finished garment radically!</p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation Tables of All Parameters Required:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sun/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSun/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlina/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a> </strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation&nbsp;Tables with Fixed Parameters:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sunFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></s